Apr 4 2008	We'd stay here again!	We chose the Days Inn Waterloo as part of a British Airways flight/hotel package purchased in June 2007, and it was an excellent decision and value. I'd read the previous reviews about a crowded breakfast scene and it was easy to get around that - either come later or earlier. We had no trouble at 7 or at 9:30, and the food was consistently plentiful and tasty.The room was small but arranged very well and it was clean and comfortable and beautifully maintained. We were on the 5th floor and had a perfect view of the Eye, and though we could hear some sirens we mostly didn't notice because we already live in a city (Washington, DC). Really, the noise wasn't a big deal at all. In addition to the Tube stop there are multiple bus lines you can access within blocks, so we found this location to be extremely convenient. We would have liked to have more eateries nearby within walking distance, but the Tandoori place down the street was yummy. We will definitely stay here again the next time we come!	
Mar 22 2008 	Waterloo Sunset	We were visiting London to go to The Old Vic theatre so I booked Days as part of the package because it was the closest hotel and also because I got a good deal. Although the official book-in time was 2PM, we arrived at 11AM to at least leave our bags off, instead we were given our room right away -----which was nice.The room was just fine for what we required, it was clean (and cleaned every day) comfortable and warm. The small bathroom was clean and fresh towels were provided each day.The buffet breakfast was great value IMO, although as has been pointed out, it could get a little bit crowded at times, but if you timed it right, the high-school students had already eaten and were waiting around reception for their coaches to arrive (Hi krissy :-)) The hotel is in a good location with Lambeth North tube station just up the street (£4 from here to Heathrow) and also a good bus service (159) which will take you past Westminster, Whitehall, Trafalgar Square, Piccadilly and Regent Street, ending at Marble Arch. The road outside the hotel has shops, cafés, restaurants, chemists and there are two pubs within 200yards. Kennington Road nick is just across the street and there are major hospitals nearby so there can be a lot of siren noise, but hey, you're in the centre of a major city, it's normal. The Imperial War Museum is across the street and is well worth a visit and the London Eye is about ten minutes walk.I enjoyed my four-day stay at Days and I would definitely stay there again.PS. Spacey and Goldblum were awesome!!	
Mar 12 2008	A decent budget hotel	I am a teacher and 4 of my colleagues and I accompanied a group of 27 high school students for a week trip in England. We stayed at the Days Hotel for 6 nights. Even though our group was large, the check-in was efficient. The rooms were clean and comfortable. The location of the hotel was good and it was only a 2 minute walk to Lambeth North tube station. We even had a view of the London Eye from our room which was especially pretty at night. I recommend asking for a room facing the London Eye!The buffet breakfast was well stocked and very tasty. The choices included eggs, bacon, sausages, beans, grilled tomatoes, freshly baked pastries, croissants, and rolls, a variety of cheeses, yogurt, fresh fruit, and cereal. There was also a coffee/hot chocolate machine and juice and milk available. The breakfast room was busy but we always found a seat. The breakfast was definitely worth it!My one complaint about the hotel was the shower. The water in the shower was never hot enough (it was just lukewarm), and the drain seemed clogged.However, the staff was accommodating and even let us use another room to shower one morning when there was no hot water.This was a great place to stay with teenagers, and it seems to be a popular place amongst tour groups,which might not be good if you are looking for an absolutely quiet hotel experience.Overall, the Days Waterloo was a clean, well-situated no-frills hotel.	
